2026-04-11 | Count Strictly Increasing Subarrays

	Question
Return number of strictly increasing subarrays.

	Approach
1.	Traverse array and maintain length of current increasing segment:
		len = length of current increasing subarray  

2.	If arr[i] > arr[i-1]:
		len++  
	else:
		reset len = 1  

3.	For each position:
		add (len - 1) to answer  
		(because subarrays ending here of size ≥2)

	Why?
	If current increasing length = L:
		number of subarrays ending here = L-1  

4.	Sum all contributions  

	Time Complexity
	O(n)

	Space Complexity
	O(1)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    int countIncreasingSubarrays(vector<int>& arr) {

        int n = arr.size();
        int len = 1;
        int ans = 0;

        for(int i = 1; i < n; i++){

            if(arr[i] > arr[i-1]){
                len++;
            } else {
                len = 1;
            }

            ans += (len - 1);
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

	Key Insight
Every increasing segment of length L contributes:
		L*(L-1)/2 subarrays  

Instead of computing separately,
we accumulate incrementally using:
		ans += (len - 1)  

This gives an optimal O(n) solution.
